to 1803","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","1395":"1395","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales":"Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales","Austria":"Austria","Austria, Hungary":"Hungary","Vienna, Austria":"Vienna, Austria","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Dafydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Salop","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Laurent, Marcel, Nicolle, Serge.  Spanish Alberto, Aurelio, Dionisio, Elvira, Fernando, Florentino, Jose, Orlando.  Italian Aldo, Antonio, Francesca, Francesco, Gennaro, Mauro.","French: habitational name from any of several places called Salon(s), for example in Dordogne and Bouches-du-Rhône.","Perhaps an Americanized form of Italian   Salone  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Salone","meanings":["form of an unrecorded Aramaic name, akin to the Hebrew word <i>shalom</i> ‘peace’. It was common at the time of Christ, and was borne by one of the women who were at his tomb and witnessed the Resurrection (Mark 16:1–8). This would normally have led to its common use as a Christian name, and it is indeed found as such in medieval times. However, according to the Jewish historian Josephus, it was also the name of King Herod's stepdaughter, the daughter of Queen Herodias. In the Bible, a daughter of Herodias, generally identified as this Salome, danced for Herod and so pleased him that he offered to give her anything she wanted. Prompted by her mother, she asked for (and got) the head of John the Baptist, who was in one of Herod's prisons (Mark 6:17–28). This story so gripped medieval imagination that the name Salome became more or less taboo until the end of the 19th century, when  Oscar Wilde  wrote a play about her and some unconventional souls began to choose the name for their daughters."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dafydd Salop ap Gruffudd was born in 1425, in Vienna, Austria, his father, Gruffudd ap Jerwerth, was 30 and his mother, Margaret ferch Llewelyn, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Angharad ferch Maredudd. He died in 1455, in Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1425–1455":"1425–1455","1420–1455":"1420–1455","1423–1455":"1423–1455","1463–1485":"1463–1485","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1425":"1425","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","from 1230 to 1803":"from 1230 to 1803","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","1395":"1395","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales":"Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales","Austria":"Austria","Austria, Hungary":"Ungari","Vienna, Austria":"Wien, Austria"},"fi":{"1425–1455":"1425–1455","1420–1455":"1420–1455","1423–1455":"1423–1455","1463–1485":"1463–1485","1395–Male":"1395–Kuollut","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1425":"1425","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","from 1230 to 1803":"vuodesta 1230 vuoteen 1803","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","1395":"1395","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales":"Carrog, Merionethshire, Wales","Austria":"Itävalta","Austria, Hungary":"Unkari","Vienna, Austria":"Wien, Itävalta"},"fr":{"1425–1455":"1425–1455","1420–1455":"1420–1455","1423–1